					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mayoculpa" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3489662); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3489662&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251150" alt="mayoculpa" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3489662)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mayoculpa" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3489662); return false;" >mayoculpa</a></span> <span class="odate time_1546702356 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Jan 2019 15:32</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4109434">
									

<p>Yes, great catch and thank you for double checking that! Will fix it right away. I had dug into the articles on giant tube worms and their close annelid relatives for my terminology, but hadn't looked up chemotropism specifically.</p>
<p>When I was in school they were still calling single celled organisms that can metabolize hydrogen sulfide &quot;archaebacteria&quot; which threw me for a loop at first. So when I say &quot;achieving bacterial chemosynthesis&quot; in the footnote it's not the most precise description scientifically. I figured it was close enough to get readers started if they wanted to look up the science parts, while still being immediately understandable. The Wikipedia articles on these animals did not provide much in the way of detail I could use for a restaurant menu, but I doubt they've been described as if they were food very often before. :3</p>

							</div>

								
					
